Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

Developed by Monica Iddah¶

Introduction¶

Prosper Loan is a loan services system that renders loan to people from all round the united states.

The loan application system contains 113,937 applications with 81 different types of information or variables. The variables in the dataset include but not limited to:(ListingCreationDate, ListingNumber, ListingKey, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, Occupation, IncomeRange, StatedMonthlyIncome, IncomeVerifiable, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate, MonthlyLoanPayment, DateCreditPulled, Recommendations, LoanStatus, Term, PercentFunded, ClosedDate, IsBorrowerHomeowner, InvestmentFromFriendsCount, InvestmentFromFriendsAmount, Investors)

The dataset would be explored upon the listed variables in the following three dimensions (Univariate, Bivariate and Multivariate exploration) inorder to achieve the correlation and relationship there exist amongst the dataset.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The libraries neccessary for the analysis would be imported and the dataset would be read in .csv file format

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 Loan application with 22 different types of information list provided (ListingCreationDate, ListingNumber, ListingKey, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, Occupation, IncomeRange, StatedMonthlyIncome, IncomeVerifiable, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate, MonthlyLoanPayment, DateCreditPulled, Recommendations, LoanStatus, Term, PercentFunded, ClosedDate, IsBorrowerHomeowner, InvestmentFromFriendsCount, InvestmentFromFriendsAmount, Investors).

The dataset was read in, the variables to be explored were listed and I had to reorder them to fit in my story line.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out the features that make a loan application successfull over the unsuccessful loan applications

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

A verrified source of income would most likely guarantee a successfull loan application and payback.

Univariate Exploration¶

Rubric Tip: Use the "Question-Visualization-Observations" framework throughout the exploration. This framework involves asking a question from the data, creating a visualization to find answers, and then recording observations after each visualisation.

In [72]:
# A histogram plot function with default bin size
               
def hist_plot(dataframe, feature, title, x_label, y_label):   
        plt.figure(figsize = [20, 10])
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.hist(data = dataframe, x = feature)
        plt.title(title, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xticks(size = 10)
        plt.yticks(size = 10)
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        
def hist_plot2(dataframe, feature, title, x_label, y_label): 
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.hist(data = dataframe, x = feature, bins = 30)
        plt.title(title, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xticks(size = 10)
        plt.yticks(size = 10)
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        
        
def bar_plot(dataframe, feature, title, x_label, y_label):   
        plt.figure(figsize = [20, 10])
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.hist(data = dataframe, x = feature)
        plt.title(title, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xticks(size = 10)
        plt.yticks(size = 10)
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        
def bar_plot2(dataframe, feature, title, x_label, y_label): 
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.hist(data = dataframe, x = feature, bins = 30)
        plt.title(title, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 15)
        plt.xticks(size = 10)
        plt.yticks(size = 10)
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)

Univariate Summary¶

The IncomeVerifiable variable showed a very clear analysis of why more of the loans applied for were successful as more borrowers income were verified than not, keeping the loan company at a profit.

We also saw that most of the loans have been completed (closed), because a payback was done within stipulated timing. There were other features that made loan application successfull suc as, a borrowers occupation, their eemployment status and their collateral (Owning a home)

Before exploring the dataset, I had to change some datatypes inorder to suit my analysis, like naming the categorical datatypes over the numeric datatypes.

I also had to change the datatypes of the time piece variables to datetime, so that we can filter just the year in the analysis of the loan creation date and closed date. It was initially displaying my output in timestamp format.

The univariate visualizations was done, analyzing single variables at a time.

Bivariate Exploration¶

On to the Bivariate visualization, my analysis would be based on the variables previously raised in the Univariate exploration. We would investigate the relationships between pairs of variables in our dataset.

Below functions for the bivariate exploration are declared.¶

# A scatter plot functor
def biplot_scatter(dataframe, x_value, y_value, title, x_label, y_label):
    plt.figure(figsize = [25,10])
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sb.scatterplot(data = dataframe, x = x_value, y = y_value)
    #plt.scatter(data = dataframe, x = x_value, y = y_value)
    plt.title(title, size = 20)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, size = 20)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, size = 20)
    plt.xticks(size = 15)
    plt.yticks(size = 15)

# A scatter plot function with alpha value
def biplot_scatter2(dataframe, x_value, y_value, title, x_label, y_label):
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sb.scatterplot(data = dataframe, x = x_value, y = y_value, alpha = 1/10)
    plt.title(title, size = 20)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, size = 20)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, size = 20)
    plt.xticks(size = 15)
    plt.yticks(size = 15)
    
# A seaborn count plot function
# If there is no plotting order, use None as the last argument
def bicount_plot(dataframe, feature, hue, title, x_label, y_label, order):
    plt.figure(figsize = [15, 10])
    ax = sb.countplot(data = dataframe, x = feature, hue = hue, order = order)
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 15)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(size = 15)
    plt.yticks(size = 15);
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate('{:.3f}%'.format((p.get_height()/df.shape[0])*100), (p.get_x()+0, p.get_height()+5),
                   ha = 'left', va = 'center_baseline', xytext = (0, 9), textcoords = 'offset points')
